<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="1657" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[160,1156,141,271]" box="[160,285,141,167]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657">
<heading bold="true" box="[160,285,141,167]" fontSize="11" level="4" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657" reason="0">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,285,141,167]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[160,1156,141,271]" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657">
The specific name is taken from the characteristically narrow frons of the male of this species, and is formed from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[665,768,213,236]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657">angustus</emphasis>
, meaning narrow, plus the Latin 
<emphasis box="[160,217,247,271]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="1657">frons</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
